In SQL, a JOIN is used to combine rows from two or more tables based on a related column between them.

Think of joins like matching data from different tables using a common key.

🔑 Why joins are needed

In real databases, data is split into multiple tables to avoid duplication.

Example:

Customers table → customer info
Orders table → order info

To see which customer placed which order, you use a JOIN.

📊 Types of SQL Joins
1. INNER JOIN

Returns only the rows that have matching values in both tables.

SELECT *
FROM Customers
INNER JOIN Orders
ON Customers.customer_id = Orders.customer_id;

👉 Only matching records appear
👉 Non-matching rows are excluded

2. LEFT JOIN (LEFT OUTER JOIN)

Returns all rows from the left table + matching rows from the right table.

SELECT *
FROM Customers
LEFT JOIN Orders
ON Customers.customer_id = Orders.customer_id;

👉 All customers are shown
👉 If no order exists → NULL values for Orders

3. RIGHT JOIN (RIGHT OUTER JOIN)

Returns all rows from the right table + matching rows from the left.

SELECT *
FROM Customers
RIGHT JOIN Orders
ON Customers.customer_id = Orders.customer_id;

👉 All orders are shown
👉 If no customer match → NULL for customer fields

4. FULL JOIN (FULL OUTER JOIN)

Returns all rows from both tables.

SELECT *
FROM Customers
FULL JOIN Orders
ON Customers.customer_id = Orders.customer_id;

👉 Includes:

Matching rows
Non-matching from left
Non-matching from right

5. CROSS JOIN

Returns the Cartesian product (every combination of rows).

SELECT *
FROM Customers
CROSS JOIN Orders;

👉 If 3 customers and 4 orders → 12 rows
👉 Usually used carefully

🧠 Simple Example

Customers
| id | name  |
| -- | ----- |
| 1  | Alice |
| 2  | Bob   |


Orders
| id  | customer_id |
| --- | ----------- |
| 101 | 1           |
| 102 | 3           |


INNER JOIN result:
| name  | order_id |
| ----- | -------- |
| Alice | 101      |

LEFT JOIN result:
| name  | order_id |
| ----- | -------- |
| Alice | 101      |
| Bob   | NULL     |


🧾 Summary
Join Type	Returns
INNER JOIN	Only matching rows
LEFT JOIN	All left + matches
RIGHT JOIN	All right + matches
FULL JOIN	Everything
CROSS JOIN	All combinations
